WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.220 --> 00:00:04.800
All right, I'll make it super fast.

00:00:05.940 --> 00:00:09.510
It's me, Destin. Welcome back to SmarterEveryDay. When you're in a jet, if the

00:00:09.510 --> 00:00:12.709
cabin depressurizes, they drop this
little mask out of the top.

00:00:12.719 --> 00:00:16.139
What happens if you're in a depressurized
cabin and you're up above 15,000 feet [4,500m]

00:00:16.139 --> 00:00:21.869
and you drop your mask? Something called
hypoxia takes effect and you got to do

00:00:21.869 --> 00:00:23.039
something about that.

00:00:23.039 --> 00:00:24.239
Let's get smarter every day.

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:30.260
You've heard the flight attendants say
this before,

00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:33.780
“Secure your own mask before helping others.” But why?

00:00:34.140 --> 00:00:36.820
Why did they say
that? Is the 30 seconds it takes to put

00:00:36.829 --> 00:00:39.739
on a kid’s mask next to me really that
important?

00:00:39.739 --> 00:00:42.620
15 years ago I learned the answer to
this question when I was selected to

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:46.040
participate in NASA’s Reduced Gravity
Student Flight Opportunities Program at

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:49.670
NASA’s Johnson Space Center. Before I got
to ride in the Vomit Comet I had to

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:53.239
undergo physiological training in a
hypobaric chamber at the neutral

00:00:53.239 --> 00:00:54.500
buoyancy lab.

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:59.000
Fast forward to now. Today, astronaut Don
Pettit is scheduled to renew his hypoxia

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.299
training certification and I asked him
if it would be okay if I tagged along

00:01:02.300 --> 00:01:05.540
let me swim a few laps with him over the
International Space Station mock-up in

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:09.350
the neutral buoyancy lab before we
headed over next door for Don’s training.

00:01:09.350 --> 00:01:13.390
– You look like something the dog dragged in.
– I feel like it, too.
The purpose

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:16.970
of hypoxia training is to let astronauts
and aviators know when their brain’s

00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:21.200
about to stop working correctly, which is very, very important. If you’re at a high

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:25.100
altitude in an airplane, the air is
thinner but the cabin is pressurized, so

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:29.540
your body gets enough oxygen to operate. To simulate cabin depressurization, NASA

00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:33.830
puts its astronauts in a chamber at
sea level and then pumps the air out to

00:01:33.830 --> 00:01:36.560
thin it out, so that it simulates a
higher altitude.

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:39.980
Don’s training starts with class work
focused on understanding the specific

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:43.130
signs and symptoms of hypoxia in his own body.

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:46.610
The goal of this training is to understand
your own physiological symptoms so that

00:01:46.610 --> 00:01:48.170
you can take action quickly.

00:01:48.170 --> 00:01:51.680
For example, Don said he experiences
tunnel vision and air hunger, but I

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:54.920
remember for my training 15 years ago
that get really happy and start to

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:56.180
tingle all over

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:59.600
– I can't take you seriously because this
is what you look like.

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:01.790
– What do you mean? I look perfectly normal.
– [giggling]

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:04.820
This is the experiment we're going to do:
Don and I are both going to enter the

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:08.450
hypobaric chamber at the same time and
fly to FL250, at which point we are

00:02:08.450 --> 00:02:11.599
going to remove our masks and start to
experience the effects of hypoxia.

00:02:12.319 --> 00:02:16.310
Don is the control. He’s a trained
astronaut who recognizes the symptoms

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:19.069
for hypoxia and immediately corrects for them.

00:02:19.069 --> 00:02:23.239
I, on the other hand, am under the direct supervision of a NASA flight surgeon and

00:02:23.239 --> 00:02:25.220
after I notice the effects of hypoxia,

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:28.790
I’ve asked if I could delay for about
one minute so we can better understand

00:02:28.790 --> 00:02:32.180
the physiological effects of not
immediately putting your mask on.

00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:33.860
OK, here we go, we're getting set up.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:36.800
While Jerry gets me situated, I’m
going to talk about the two types of

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:40.500
decompression: Number one, rapid
decompression this is like being inside

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:41.940
of an explosion.

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:44.920
You dump all your pressure instantly, all
the moisture condenses out of the air,

00:02:44.920 --> 00:02:48.100
you’re suddenly in a cloud.
Very scary, very violent

00:02:48.120 --> 00:02:51.030
Yeah, we’re not going to do that.
What we're going to do is simulate a slow,

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:55.440
steady leak. We’re going to start at sea
level and ascend at 5,000 feet [1,500m] per minute

00:02:55.440 --> 00:03:00.510
all the way up to 25,000 feet [7,500m], or as aviators call it, flight level 250

